Grammar of graphics Plotting framework - Graphics = distinct layers of grammatical elements - Meaningful plots through aesthetic mapping

7 grammatical elements Data Aesthetics - axis/scale Geometrics - visual elements for data Facets - small multiples Statistics - Understanding statistical significance of data Coordinates - Space on which the data is plotted Themes - Non data ink

Exploring ggplot2 plotting

# 1 - The plot you created in the previous exercise
ggplot(diamonds, aes(x = carat, y = price)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth()

# 2 - Copy the above command but show only the smooth line
ggplot(diamonds, aes(x = carat, y = price)) +
  geom_smooth()

# 3 - Copy the above command and assign the correct value to col in aes()
ggplot(diamonds, aes(x = carat, y = price, colour=clarity)) +
  geom_smooth()

# 4 - Keep the color settings from previous command. Plot only the points with argument alpha.
ggplot(diamonds, aes(x = carat, y = price, colour=clarity)) +
  geom_point(alpha=0.4)

# Create the object containing the data and aes layers: dia_plot
dia_plot <- ggplot(diamonds, aes(x = carat, y = price))
# Add a geom layer with + and geom_point()
dia_plot + geom_point()

# Add the same geom layer, but with aes() inside
dia_plot + geom_point(aes(color = clarity))

Adding additional smoothening functions:

# 1 - The dia_plot object has been created for you
dia_plot <- ggplot(diamonds, aes(x = carat, y = price))
# 2 - Expand dia_plot by adding geom_point() with alpha set to 0.2
dia_plot + geom_point(alpha=0.2)

# 3 - Plot dia_plot with additional geom_smooth() with se set to FALSE
dia_plot + geom_smooth(se = F)

# 4 - Copy the command from above and add aes() with the correct mapping to geom_smooth()
dia_plot + geom_smooth(aes(col = clarity), se = F)

Plot function linear model Key takeaways: Using base package plot function, we can add the linear model, however, it is a tedious task since we have to add legend manually

# Use lm() to calculate a linear model and save it as carModel
carModel <- lm(mpg ~ wt, data = mtcars)

  geom_point()  # Fill in using instructions Plot 1

# Plot 2: include the lines of the linear models, per cyl
ggplot(mtcars, aes(x = wt, y = mpg, col = cyl)) +
  geom_point() + # Copy from Plot 1
  geom_smooth(method='lm', se=F)   # Fill in using instructions Plot 2

# Plot 3: include a lm for the entire dataset in its whole
ggplot(mtcars, aes(x = wt, y = mpg, col = cyl)) +
  geom_point() + # Copy from Plot 2
  geom_smooth(method = 'lm', se=F) + # Copy from Plot 2
  geom_smooth(aes(group=1), method='lm', se=F, linetype=2)  # Fill in using instructions Plot 3

Aesthetics X and Y axis mappings aes - aes def attributes - geom layer col fill - fill colour size alpha linetype - has pattern labels - text on plot or axes

## Playing around with aesthetics
# 1 - Map mpg to x and cyl to y
ggplot(mtcars, aes(mpg, cyl)) +
  geom_point()

  
# 2 - Reverse: Map cyl to x and mpg to y
ggplot(mtcars, aes(cyl, mpg)) +
  geom_point()

# 3 - Map wt to x, mpg to y and cyl to col
ggplot(mtcars, aes(wt, mpg, col=cyl)) +
  geom_point()

# 4 - Change shape and size of the points in the above plot
ggplot(mtcars, aes(wt, mpg, col=cyl)) +
  geom_point(shape=1,size=4)

my_color <- "#4ABEFF"

# 2 - Plot 1, but set col attributes in geom layer:
ggplot(mtcars, aes(wt, mpg, col=cyl)) + geom_point(col=my_color)

# 3 - Plot 2, with fill instead of col aesthetic, plut shape and size attributes in geom layer.
ggplot(mtcars, aes(wt, mpg, fill=cyl)) + geom_point(size=10, shape= 23, col=my_color)

Playing with color and label

# Expand to draw points with alpha 0.5

# Expand to draw points with shape 24 and color yellow
ggplot(mtcars, aes(x = wt, y = mpg, fill = cyl)) + geom_point(shape=24, colour="yellow")

  
# Expand to draw text with label rownames(mtcars) and color red
ggplot(mtcars, aes(x = wt, y = mpg, fill = cyl)) +
  geom_text(label = rownames(mtcars), color = 'red')

Advanced graphics using ggplot

# Map mpg onto x, qsec onto y and factor(cyl) onto col
ggplot(mtcars, aes(mpg, qsec, col=factor(cyl)))+geom_point()

# Add mapping: factor(am) onto shape
ggplot(mtcars, aes(mpg, qsec,shape=factor(am), col=factor(cyl)))+ geom_point()

# Add mapping: (hp/wt) onto size
ggplot(mtcars, aes(mpg, qsec,size=(hp/wt), shape=factor(am), col=factor(cyl)))+ geom_point()

Modifying aesthetics

Position - identity - value in dataframe witll pe plotted like data jittering - adding random noise to identify density position_jitter(width=0.1) scale_ - check and modify the scales of plot

scale_ args - name, limit, breaks, expand, labels labs()

# The base layer, cyl.am, is available for you
cyl.am <- ggplot(mtcars, aes(x = factor(cyl), fill = factor(am)))
# Add geom (position = "stack" by default)
cyl.am + 
  geom_bar()

# Fill - show proportion
cyl.am + 
  geom_bar(position = "fill")  

# Dodging - principles of similarity and proximity
cyl.am +
  geom_bar(position ="dodge") 

# Clean up the axes with scale_ functions
val = c("#E41A1C", "#377EB8")
lab = c("Manual", "Automatic")
cyl.am +
  geom_bar(position = "dodge") +
  scale_x_discrete("Cylinders") + 
  scale_y_continuous("Number") +
  scale_fill_manual("Transmission", 
                    values = val,
                    labels = lab)

Adding scales to make the plot appropriately sized

# 1 - Create jittered plot of mtcars, mpg onto x, 0 onto y
ggplot(mtcars, aes(x = mpg, y = 0)) +
  geom_jitter()

# 2 - Add function to change y axis limits
ggplot(mtcars, aes(x = mpg, y = 0)) +
  geom_jitter()+
  scale_y_continuous(limits=c(-2,2))

Aesthetic best practices Function - important to identify audience, plot accordingly, data should be represented accurately in the plot Form - visual aesthetics

Continuous variables - scatter plots (position) color - not ideal for continuous variables size - not ideal

Aligned scales - very important(juxtaposed on same axis)

Categorical variables Color/Size - use should not lead to confusion or excess of information

# Basic scatter plot: wt on x-axis and mpg on y-axis; map cyl to col
cyl_fac<-as.factor(mtcars$cyl)
ggplot(mtcars, aes(wt, mpg, col=cyl_fac))+geom_point(size=4)

# Hollow circles - an improvement
ggplot(mtcars, aes(wt, mpg, col=cyl_fac))+geom_point(shape=1, size=4)

# Add transparency - very nice
ggplot(mtcars, aes(wt, mpg, col=cyl_fac))+geom_point(alpha=0.6, size=4)

# Scatter plot: carat (x), price (y), clarity (color)

ggplot(diamonds, aes(carat, price, col=clarity))+geom_point(alpha=0.5)

# Scatter plot: clarity (x), carat (y), price (color)
ggplot(diamonds, aes(clarity, carat, col=price))+geom_point(alpha=0.5)

# Dot plot with jittering
ggplot(diamonds, aes(clarity, carat, col=price))+geom_point(alpha=0.5, position="jitter")

Common plots scatter plots bar plots line plots

scatter plots - geom_point(aes(x,y)) overplotting solutions - add jitter, add hollow circles

# Shown in the viewer:
ggplot(mtcars, aes(x = cyl, y = wt)) +
  geom_point()

# Solutions:
# 1 - With geom_jitter()
ggplot(mtcars, aes(x = cyl, y = wt)) +
  geom_jitter()

# 2 - Set width in geom_jitter()
ggplot(mtcars, aes(x = cyl, y = wt)) +
  geom_jitter(width=0.1)

# 3 - Set position = position_jitter() in geom_point() ()
ggplot(mtcars, aes(x = cyl, y = wt)) +
  geom_point(position = position_jitter(0.1))

# 1 - Make a univariate histogram
ggplot(mtcars, aes(x = mpg)) +
  geom_histogram()

ggplot(mtcars, aes(x = mpg)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth=1)

# 3 - Plot 2, plus MAP ..density.. to the y aesthetic (i.e. in a second aes() function)
ggplot(mtcars, aes(x = mpg)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth=1, aes(y=..density..))

# 4 - plot 3, plus SET the fill attribute to "#377EB8"

  geom_histogram(binwidth=1, aes(y=..density..), fill="#377EB8")

Qplot

simpler than ggplot is better for easy plots , less flexible than ggplot2 NOTES: There is no actual difference between the ggplot and qplot. Base plot defaults are slightly different. Plots 1 and 2 are base, 3 and 4 are ggplot

#Basic Q plot
# The old way (shown)
plot(mpg ~ wt, data = mtcars) # formula notation

with(mtcars, plot(wt, mpg)) # x, y notation

# Using ggplot:
ggplot(mtcars, aes(wt, mpg)) +
  geom_point()

# Using qplot:
qplot(wt, mpg, data = mtcars)

Aesthetics in qplot

# basic qplot scatter plot:
qplot(wt, mpg, data = mtcars)

# Categorical variable mapped onto size:
# cyl
qplot(wt, mpg, data = mtcars, size = factor(cyl))

# gear
qplot(wt, mpg, data = mtcars, size = factor(gear))

# Continuous variable mapped onto col:
# hp
qplot(wt, mpg, data = mtcars, col = hp)

# qsec
qplot(wt, mpg, data = mtcars, col = qsec)

Jitter inside the function call

# qplot() with x only
qplot(factor(cyl), data=mtcars)

# qplot() with x and y
qplot(factor(cyl),factor(vs), data=mtcars)

# qplot() with geom set to jitter manually
qplot(factor(cyl), factor(vs), data=mtcars, geom="jitter")

  factor(cyl), wt,
  data = mtcars,
  fill = factor(am),
  geom = "dotplot",
  binaxis = "y",
  stackdir = "center"
)
